Anyway, the game was well worth the wait and the second quest may be fun, but later, much later. I've played the game far too much.. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caster8516>Caster8516</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(4/9/03 7:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=633.topic&index=33>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Blargh</span><hr size=1> At first, I was skeptical as to whether Zelda would be worth buying or not, because after seeing the more realistic rendition of the game in the early stages of the Gamecube, I was severely let down with the more childish graphics of the New Zelda. I was pretty angry that they got rid of the one concept, but then that anger turned to curiosity, and then curiosity turned to excitement. Not only are the cell shaded graphics excelent, but the animation is just as good. The movement is fluid and perfect. The backround is just as good, if not better. It can annoy me from time to time though, because the backround is often out of focus in large areas to show distance. It just gives my eyes some problems. The battle system is a good deal better, and I think the game is a lot more action oriented. The only real fights you had back in Ocarina of Time were those skeletons at night - at least the only fights I enjoyed (the lizard men were also fun). Now, you have many combatants to sqaure off against, and there are different tactics you must use to fight them. There's a nice mix of strategy and skill.<br>
       However, with all this joy to be had, I am extremely sad. I have had around two to three hours of gameplay in Zelda. The gamecube I own is roughly a year and a half old. When I get to the top of the Dragon's roost, I pull a &quot;Cannot read Disk error&quot; every time I enter new area's. I have cleaned the lense, the game, checked the disks, and checked the other disks. It seems the problem lies within the cube, and most likely with the lense. Sending it to be fixed is $75, and I don't want to buy a new one because I have this suspiscion that that's exactly what Nintendo wants. Perhaps they planned the cube to break down within two years (exceeding warrenty), and made it a pain in the ass to fix. All I know, is I can't play a wonderful game, and will have to pay out the ass to play the thing. Woe is me.<br>
